so that it follows I am roughand lecherous.

529
00:28:43.530 --> 00:28:45.970
I should have been that I am,

530
00:28:45.970 --> 00:28:48.500
had the maidenliest star in thefirmament twinkled

531
00:28:48.500 --> 00:28:50.270
on my bastardizing.

532
00:28:50.270 --> 00:28:51.370
Edgar

533
00:28:52.700 --> 00:28:55.800
Pat he comes like thecatastrophe of the old comedy.

534
00:28:55.800 --> 00:28:58.430
My cue is villainous melancholy,

535
00:28:58.430 --> 00:29:02.300
with a sigh like Tom o' Bedlam.

536
00:29:02.300 --> 00:29:11.770
O, these eclipses do portendthese divisions.

537
00:29:15.870 --> 00:29:17.600
How now, brother Edmund?

538
00:29:20.830 --> 00:29:23.000
What serious contemplation areyou in?

539
00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:24.300
I am thinking, brother,

540
00:29:24.300 --> 00:29:26.130
of a prediction I read thisother day

541
00:29:26.130 --> 00:29:28.130
what should follow theseeclipses.

542
00:29:28.130 --> 00:29:29.730
Do you busy yourself with that?

543
00:29:29.730 --> 00:29:34.530
I promise you, the effects hewrites of succeed unhappily,

544
00:29:34.530 --> 00:29:38.430
as of unnaturalness between thechild and the parent;

545
00:29:38.430 --> 00:29:44.170
death, dearth, dissolutions ofancient amities;

546
00:29:44.170 --> 00:29:45.430
divisions in state;

547
00:29:45.430 --> 00:29:48.770
menaces and maledictions againstking and nobles;

548
00:29:48.770 --> 00:29:52.600
needless diffidences; banishmentof friends;

549
00:29:52.600 --> 00:29:56.070
dissipation of cohorts; nuptialbreaches;

550
00:29:56.070 --> 00:29:57.270
and I know not what.

551
00:29:57.270 --> 00:29:59.170
How long have you been a sectaryastronomical?

552
00:29:59.170 --> 00:30:00.400
Come, come.

553
00:30:04.230 --> 00:30:06.630
When saw you my father last?

554
00:30:06.630 --> 00:30:08.270
The night gone by.

555
00:30:08.270 --> 00:30:09.300
Spake you with him?

556
00:30:09.300 --> 00:30:10.730
Ay, two hours together.

557
00:30:10.730 --> 00:30:13.500
Parted you in good terms?

558
00:30:13.500 --> 00:30:17.130
Found you no displeasure in himby word nor countenance?

559
00:30:17.130 --> 00:30:18.400
None at all.

560
00:30:18.400 --> 00:30:21.500
Bethink yourself wherein you mayhave offended him.

561
00:30:21.500 --> 00:30:23.670
And at my entreaty, forbear hispresence

562
00:30:23.670 --> 00:30:25.700
until some little time hathqualified the heat

563
00:30:25.700 --> 00:30:26.770
of his displeasure,

564
00:30:26.770 --> 00:30:29.430
which, at this instant, sorageth in him

565
00:30:29.430 --> 00:30:31.770
that with the mischief of yourperson,

566
00:30:31.770 --> 00:30:32.800
it would scarcely allay.

567
00:30:32.800 --> 00:30:34.130
Some villain hath done me wrong.

568
00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:36.470
That's my fear.

569
00:30:36.470 --> 00:30:39.430
I pray you, have a continentforbearance

570
00:30:39.430 --> 00:30:41.400
till the speed of his rage goesslower.

571
00:30:41.400 --> 00:30:45.770
And, as I say, retire with me tomy lodging,

572
00:30:45.770 --> 00:30:48.630
from whence I will fitly bringyou to hear my lord speak.

573
00:30:48.630 --> 00:30:50.230
Pray ye, go.

574
00:30:50.230 --> 00:30:52.900
There's my key.

575
00:30:52.900 --> 00:30:55.330
If you do stir abroad, go armed.

576
00:30:55.330 --> 00:30:56.670
Armed, brother?

577
00:30:56.670 --> 00:30:59.770
Brother, I advise you to thebest.

578
00:30:59.770 --> 00:31:02.500
I am no honest man if there beany good meaning toward you.

579
00:31:02.500 --> 00:31:04.330
I have told you what I have seenand heard,

580
00:31:04.330 --> 00:31:06.970
but faintly nothing like theimage and horror of it.

581
00:31:06.970 --> 00:31:08.400
Pray you, away.

582
00:31:08.400 --> 00:31:09.500
Shall I hear from you anon?

583
00:31:09.500 --> 00:31:12.900
I do serve you in this business.

584
00:31:26.930 --> 00:31:31.030
A credulous father and a brothernoble,

585
00:31:31.030 --> 00:31:33.100
whose nature is so far fromdoing harms

586
00:31:33.100 --> 00:31:34.870
that he suspects none,

587
00:31:34.870 --> 00:31:39.300
on whose foolish honesty mypractices ride easy.

588
00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:41.670
I see the business.

589
00:31:41.670 --> 00:31:44.670
Let me, if not by birth, havelands by wit.

590
00:31:44.670 --> 00:31:47.630
All with me's meet that I canfashion fit.

591
00:31:57.770 --> 00:31:59.130
Did my father strike mygentleman

592
00:31:59.130 --> 00:32:00.370
for chiding of his fool?

593
00:32:00.370 --> 00:32:01.730
Aye, madam.

594
00:32:01.730 --> 00:32:03.630
By day and night, he wrongs me.

595
00:32:03.630 --> 00:32:05.700
Every hour, he flashes into onegross crime or other

596
00:32:05.700 --> 00:32:07.700
that sets us all at odds.

597
00:32:07.700 --> 00:32:08.770
I'll not endure it.

598
00:32:08.770 --> 00:32:10.630
His knights grow riotous,

599
00:32:10.630 --> 00:32:13.400
and himself upbraids us on everytrifle.

600
00:32:13.400 --> 00:32:16.730
When he returns from hunting, Iwill not speak with him.

601
00:32:16.730 --> 00:32:18.630
Say I am sick.

602
00:32:18.630 --> 00:32:21.130
If you come slack of formerservices,

603
00:32:21.130 --> 00:32:22.270
you shall do well.

604
00:32:22.270 --> 00:32:24.330
The fault of it, I'll answer.

605
00:32:24.330 --> 00:32:26.370
He's coming, madam; I hear him.

606
00:32:26.370 --> 00:32:28.630
Put on what weary negligence youplease,

607
00:32:28.630 --> 00:32:30.200
you and your fellows.

608
00:32:30.200 --> 00:32:31.530
I'll have it come to question.

609
00:32:31.530 --> 00:32:34.900
If he distaste it, let him to mysister,

610
00:32:34.900 --> 00:32:37.700
whose mind and mine, I know, inthat are one,

611
00:32:37.700 --> 00:32:39.730
not to be over-ruled.

612
00:32:39.730 --> 00:32:44.370
Idle old man that still wouldmanage

613
00:32:44.370 --> 00:32:47.100
those authorities that he hathgiven away.

614
00:32:47.100 --> 00:32:51.830
Now, by my life, old fools arebabes again

615
00:32:51.830 --> 00:32:54.330
and must be used with checks asflatteries

616
00:32:54.330 --> 00:32:56.930
when they are seen abused.

617
00:32:56.930 --> 00:32:58.430
Remember what I have said.

618
00:32:58.430 --> 00:32:59.770
Well, madam.

619
00:32:59.770 --> 00:33:02.600
And let his knights have colderlooks among you.

620
00:33:02.600 --> 00:33:05.030
What grows of it, no matter.

621
00:33:05.030 --> 00:33:07.200
Advise your fellows so.

622
00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:10.630
I would breed from henceoccasions,

623
00:33:10.630 --> 00:33:15.200
and I shall, that I may speak.

624
00:33:15.200 --> 00:33:17.130
I'll write straight to my sister

625
00:33:17.130 --> 00:33:19.400
to hold my very course.

626
00:33:19.400 --> 00:33:21.700
Prepare for dinner.

627
00:33:25.930 --> 00:33:28.370
If but as well I other accentsborrow

628
00:33:28.370 --> 00:33:30.300
that can my speech defuse,

629
00:33:30.300 --> 00:33:32.770
my good intent may carry throughitself

630
00:33:32.770 --> 00:33:36.530
to that full issue for which Irazed my likeness.

631
00:33:38.030 --> 00:33:40.130
Now, banished Kent,

632
00:33:40.130 --> 00:33:45.130
if thou canst serve where thoudost stand condemned,

633
00:33:45.130 --> 00:33:49.430
so may it come thy master, whomthou lovest,

634
00:33:49.430 --> 00:33:52.930
shall find thee full of labors.

635
00:33:58.030 --> 00:34:00.830
Let me not stay a jot fordinner.

636
00:34:00.830 --> 00:34:03.700
Go, get it ready.

637
00:34:06.070 --> 00:34:07.270
How now?

638
00:34:07.270 --> 00:34:08.530
What art thou?

639
00:34:08.530 --> 00:34:09.700
A man, sir.

640
00:34:09.700 --> 00:34:11.500
What dost thou profess?

641
00:34:11.500 --> 00:34:12.730
What wouldst thou with us?

642
00:34:12.730 --> 00:34:14.770
I do profess to be no less thanI seem,

643
00:34:14.770 --> 00:34:16.970
to serve him truly that will putme in trust,

644
00:34:16.970 --> 00:34:18.670
to love him that is honest,

645
00:34:18.670 --> 00:34:20.770
to converse with him that iswise and says little,

646
00:34:20.770 --> 00:34:23.170
to fear judgment, to fight whenI cannot choose,

647
00:34:23.170 --> 00:34:25.030
and to eat no fish.

648
00:34:25.030 --> 00:34:26.330
What art thou?

649
00:34:26.330 --> 00:34:28.500
A very honest-hearted fellow andas poor as the king.

650
00:34:28.500 --> 00:34:31.900
If thou be as poor for a subjectas he is for a king,

651
00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:33.200
thou art poor enough.

652
00:34:33.200 --> 00:34:34.230
What wouldst thou?

653
00:34:34.230 --> 00:34:35.270
Service.

654
00:34:35.270 --> 00:34:36.300
Who wouldst thou serve?

655
00:34:36.300 --> 00:34:37.330
You.

656
00:34:37.330 --> 00:34:39.230
Dost thou know me, fellow?

657
00:34:39.230 --> 00:34:41.070
No, sir; but you have that inyour countenance

658
00:34:41.070 --> 00:34:42.930
that I would fain call master.

659
00:34:42.930 --> 00:34:44.530
What's that?

660
00:34:44.530 --> 00:34:46.500
Authority.

661
00:34:50.500 --> 00:34:51.870
What services canst thou do?

662
00:34:51.870 --> 00:34:53.930
I can keep honest counsel, ride,run,

663
00:34:53.930 --> 00:34:56.100
mar a curious tale in tellingit,

664
00:34:56.100 --> 00:34:58.030
and deliver a plain messagebluntly.

665
00:34:58.030 --> 00:35:00.270
That which ordinary men are fitfor, I am qualified in.

666
00:35:00.270 --> 00:35:02.000
And the best of me is diligence.

667
00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:03.230
How old art thou?

668
00:35:03.230 --> 00:35:05.070
Not so young, sir, to love awoman for singing,

669
00:35:05.070 --> 00:35:07.370
nor so old to dote on her foranything.

670
00:35:07.370 --> 00:35:09.000
I have years on my back 48.

671
00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:10.230
Follow me; thou shalt serve me.

672
00:35:10.230 --> 00:35:11.700
If I like thee no worse afterdinner,

673
00:35:11.700 --> 00:35:13.430
I shall not part from theebefore.

674
00:35:13.430 --> 00:35:17.530
Dinner, ho, dinner!

675
00:35:17.530 --> 00:35:19.030
Where's my knave, my fool?

676
00:35:19.030 --> 00:35:21.630
Go you, and call my fool hither.

677
00:35:21.630 --> 00:35:24.370
You, you, sirrah, where's mydaughter?

678
00:35:24.370 --> 00:35:26.330
So please you

679
00:35:29.330 --> 00:35:30.900
What says the fellow there?

680
00:35:30.900 --> 00:35:34.630
Call the clodpoll back!

681
00:35:34.630 --> 00:35:39.170
Where's my fool, ho-ho-ho?

682
00:35:40.530 --> 00:35:42.370
I think the world's asleep.

683
00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:46.170
How now!

684
00:35:46.170 --> 00:35:48.030
Where's that mongrel?

685
00:35:48.030 --> 00:35:50.330
He says, my lord, your daughteris not well.

686
00:35:50.330 --> 00:35:52.400
Why came not the slave back tome when I called him?

687
00:35:52.400 --> 00:35:54.700
Sir, he answered me in theroundest manner

688
00:35:54.700 --> 00:35:55.770
he would not.

689
00:35:58.670 --> 00:35:59.700
He would not?

690
00:35:59.700 --> 00:36:01.430
My lord, I know not what thematter is.

691
00:36:01.430 --> 00:36:02.800
But to my judgment, yourhighness

692
00:36:02.800 --> 00:36:04.900
is not entertained with thatceremonious affection

693
00:36:04.900 --> 00:36:06.300
as you were wont.

694
00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:08.470
There's a great abatement ofkindness appears as well

695
00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:09.700
in the general dependents

696
00:36:09.700 --> 00:36:11.800
as in the duke himself also andyour daughter.

697
00:36:11.800 --> 00:36:13.400
Ha! Sayest thou so?

698
00:36:13.400 --> 00:36:15.530
I beseech you, pardon me, mylord, if I be mistaken,

699
00:36:15.530 --> 00:36:16.900
for my duty cannot be silent

700
00:36:16.900 --> 00:36:18.370
when I think your highnesswronged.

701
00:36:18.370 --> 00:36:20.600
Thou but rememberest me of mineown conception.

702
00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:23.800
I have perceived a most faintneglect of late,

703
00:36:23.800 --> 00:36:27.170
which I have rather blamed asmine own jealous curiosity

704
00:36:27.170 --> 00:36:30.030
than as the very pretense andpurpose of unkindness.

705
00:36:30.030 --> 00:36:32.000
I will look further into it.

706
00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:33.130
But where's my fool?

707
00:36:33.130 --> 00:36:34.530
I have not seen him this twodays.

708
00:36:34.530 --> 00:36:36.530
Since my young lady's going intoFrance, sir,

709
00:36:36.530 --> 00:36:38.000
the fool hath much pined away.

710
00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.470
No more of that; I have noted itwell.

711
00:36:40.470 --> 00:36:42.930
Go you; tell my daughter I wouldspeak with her.

712
00:36:42.930 --> 00:36:45.600
Go you, and call hither my fool!

713
00:36:47.800 --> 00:36:51.030
O, you sir, you!

714
00:36:54.230 --> 00:36:58.200
Come you hither, sir.

715
00:37:04.100 --> 00:37:07.370
Who am I, sir?

716
00:37:07.370 --> 00:37:08.830
My lady's father.

717
00:37:08.830 --> 00:37:13.300
"My lady's father."

718
00:37:13.300 --> 00:37:15.800
My lord's knave.

719
00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:18.070
You whoreson dog, you slave, youcur.

720
00:37:18.070 --> 00:37:20.870
I am none of these, my lord; Ibeseech your pardon.

721
00:37:20.870 --> 00:37:23.530
Do you bandy looks with me, yourascal?

722
00:37:23.530 --> 00:37:25.300
I'll not be strucken, my lord.

723
00:37:25.300 --> 00:37:28.130
Nor tripped neither, you basefootball player.

724
00:37:28.130 --> 00:37:29.270
I thank thee, fellow.

725
00:37:29.270 --> 00:37:30.970
Thou servest me, and I'll lovethee.

726
00:37:30.970 --> 00:37:34.370
Come, sir. Arise, away.

727
00:37:34.370 --> 00:37:37.230
No, we'll teach you differences.

728
00:37:37.230 --> 00:37:38.600
Away, away.

729
00:37:38.600 --> 00:37:39.930
Have you wisdom?

730
00:37:39.930 --> 00:37:42.130
If you will measure yourlubber's length again, tarry.

731
00:37:42.130 --> 00:37:43.770
But away.

732
00:37:43.770 --> 00:37:46.470
Go to.

733
00:37:49.070 --> 00:37:51.170
Now, my friendly knave, I thankthee.

734
00:37:51.170 --> 00:37:54.030
Here's earnest for thy service.

735
00:37:54.030 --> 00:37:56.630
Let me hire him too: here's mycoxcomb.

736
00:37:56.630 --> 00:38:01.130
How now, my pretty knave?

737
00:38:01.130 --> 00:38:03.330
How dost thou?

738
00:38:03.330 --> 00:38:05.200
Sirrah, you were best take mycoxcomb.

739
00:38:05.200 --> 00:38:06.600
Why, fool?

740
00:38:06.600 --> 00:38:09.430
Why? For taking one's part thatout of favor.

741
00:38:09.430 --> 00:38:11.500
Nay, and thou canst not smile asthe wind sits;

742
00:38:11.500 --> 00:38:13.000
thou'lt catch cold shortly.

743
00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:14.330
Here, take my coxcomb.

744
00:38:14.330 --> 00:38:17.630
Why, this fellow, he hasbanished two on's daughters

745
00:38:17.630 --> 00:38:20.330
and did the third a blessingagainst his will.

746
00:38:20.330 --> 00:38:23.470
If thou follow him, thou mustneeds wear my coxcomb.

747
00:38:23.470 --> 00:38:24.830
How now, nuncle!

748
00:38:24.830 --> 00:38:27.670
Would I had two coxcombs and twodaughters!

749
00:38:27.670 --> 00:38:29.230
Why, boy?

750
00:38:29.230 --> 00:38:31.800
If I gave them all me living,I'ld keep my coxcombs myself.

751
00:38:31.800 --> 00:38:34.700
There's mine; beg another of thydaughters.

752
00:38:34.700 --> 00:38:37.670
Take heed, sirrah; the whip.

753
00:38:37.670 --> 00:38:39.870
Truth's a dog must to kennel.

754
00:38:39.870 --> 00:38:42.470
He must be whipped out when Ladythe brach

755
00:38:42.470 --> 00:38:44.700
may stand by the fire and stink.

756
00:38:44.700 --> 00:38:47.270
A pestilent gall to me.

757
00:38:47.270 --> 00:38:49.770
Sirrah, I'll teach thee aspeech.

758
00:38:49.770 --> 00:38:50.930
Do, boy.

759
00:38:50.930 --> 00:38:52.430
Mark it, nuncle.

760
00:38:52.430 --> 00:38:56.930
Have more than thou showest,speak less than thou knowest,

761
00:38:56.930 --> 00:39:00.600
lend less than thou owest, ridemore than thou goest,

762
00:39:00.600 --> 00:39:04.830
learn more than thou trowest,set less than thou throwest;

763
00:39:04.830 --> 00:39:07.270
leave thy drink and thy whore,and keep in-a-door,

764
00:39:07.270 --> 00:39:10.370
and thou shalt have more thantwo tens to a score.

765
00:39:10.370 --> 00:39:11.770
This is nothing, fool.

766
00:39:11.770 --> 00:39:13.930
Then 'tis like the breath of anunfee'd lawyer;

767
00:39:13.930 --> 00:39:15.630
you gave me nothing for it.

768
00:39:15.630 --> 00:39:18.770
Can you make no use of nothing,nuncle?

769
00:39:18.770 --> 00:39:22.570
Why, no, boy; nothing can bemade out of nothing.

770
00:39:22.570 --> 00:39:23.670
Prithee, tell him.

771
00:39:23.670 --> 00:39:26.200
So much the rent of his landcomes to.

772
00:39:26.200 --> 00:39:27.500
He'll not believe a fool.

773
00:39:27.500 --> 00:39:28.870
A bitter fool.

774
00:39:28.870 --> 00:39:30.930
Dost know the difference, myboy,

775
00:39:30.930 --> 00:39:33.530
between a bitter fool and asweet one?

776
00:39:33.530 --> 00:39:35.300
No, lad; teach me.

777
00:39:35.300 --> 00:39:39.430
That lord that counseled thee togive away thy land,

778
00:39:39.430 --> 00:39:42.800
come place him here by me, anddo thou for him stand.

779
00:39:42.800 --> 00:39:45.530
The sweet and bitter fool willpresently appear

780
00:39:45.530 --> 00:39:49.330
the one in motley here, theother found out there.

781
00:39:49.330 --> 00:39:51.030
Dost thou call me fool, boy?

782
00:39:51.030 --> 00:39:53.830
All thy other titles thou hastgiven away

783
00:39:53.830 --> 00:39:56.300
that thou wast born with.

784
00:39:56.300 --> 00:39:58.170
This is not altogether fool, mylord.

785
00:39:58.170 --> 00:40:00.000
No, faith, lords and great menwill not let me.

786
00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:02.500
If I had a monopoly out, they'dhave part on it.

787
00:40:02.500 --> 00:40:06.030
And the ladies too, they'll notlet me have all the fool tomyself;

788
00:40:06.030 --> 00:40:07.100
they'd be snatching.

789
00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:10.700
-Nuncle. -Huh?

790
00:40:10.700 --> 00:40:14.000
Give me an egg, and I'll givethee two crowns.

791
00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:15.300
